  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The cleansing and repairing of the temple, and the finding of the book of the law. Cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 22:3-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - In the eighteenth year of his reign, when he was purging the land and the house (of God), he sent. לטהר does not indeed signify \"after the purging\" (De Wette, with the older expositors), but still less is it a statement of the object, \"to purge\" (Berth.); for that is decisively disposed of both by its position at the beginning of the sentence, where no statement of the object would stand, but still more by the fact that a statement of the object follows, וגו לחזּק.   ל used of time denotes \"about,\" and so with the inf., e.g., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 46:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : at (his) coming  equals  when he came. Shaphan was סופר, state secretary, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
